Analyzing and Predicting Human Trafficking Data¶

Introduction¶

Human trafficking is a serious crime worldwide and affects thousands of people each year of all different ages and genders. With much of the human trafficking data being sensitive or missing, it can be difficult to find reliable and insightful analysis of the data. This tutorial walks through the data science pipeline by exploring the potential patterns and trends of the data concerning human trafficking victims, such as age, country and types of exploitation. This data is then used to attempt to predict missing data fields to project possible trends and classify human trafficking cases.

Tutorial By: Emily Son

Data Collection¶

Data Source¶

The Counter-Trafficking Data Collaborative (CTDC) has compiled a dataset of data concerning almost 50k human trafficking victims. I found this dataset on Kaggle at https://www.kaggle.com/andrewmvd/global-human-trafficking. As much of the data regarding human trafficking victims is sensitive or missing, I had some difficulty finding a dataset that was publically available and comprehensive. This dataset contains many features of each victim's case (including 63 columns/features) and almost 50k victims. Therefore, I chose this dataset as there were many features to analyze and because it is publically available.

Loading the Data¶

Because the dataset is already contained in a downloadable csv file, no curating or parsing of the data needs to be performed and it can be directly loaded into the tutorial using the pandas library.

The entire dataset, a csv file, is read into a pandas DataFrame and the missing values, denoted by -99, are replaced with NaN. The data is now in a DataFrame and can be easily viewed and manipulated throughout the tutorial.

In [2]:
# The dataset csv file is read into a pandas dataframe
# Indicating low_memory to false to get rid of warning

trafficking_table = pd.read_csv('human_trafficking.csv', low_memory=False)

Data Management/Representation¶

The missing values denoted by -99 are replaced with NaN in order to perform analysis on the data that take into account these missing values. Although not all 63 columns are explicitly used and represented in the tutorial, the more features will aid in the machine learning further into the tutorial. Therefore, they are not removed and the entire dataset is used as is to maximize the amount of data that is not missing.

In [3]:
# Missing values are denoted as a string "-99" or the number -99 depending on the type of the column. Each version 
# of missing value is replaced with NaN 

trafficking_table.replace("-99", np.nan, inplace=True)
trafficking_table.replace(-99, np.nan, inplace=True)

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

The dataset contians a lot of information and I want to analyze the different possible patterns and trends present. I approach this analysis by first gaining a better understanding of the data by visualizing some of the main features/columns with graphs and plots. Then, these plots help identify possible trends and points of interest that we might want to analyze further and test using hypothesis testing and machine learning. This part of the data science pipeline allows us to explore the data and consider what we might want to test in the next step in the pipeline.

Gender¶

Gender is the first feature that is visualized. Many people may think that only women are victims of human traffikcing. However, there are many types of human trafficking, not just sexual exploit, and men are not exempt from any of these categories. The distrubition of male and female victims, the two genders specified in the dataset, is visualized using a pie chart.

In [7]:
# Creating a dataframe of the count of female and male, grouping by gender
gender_df = pd.DataFrame(data.groupby('gender').count()['ageBroad'])

# Renaming the column to represent the count 
gender_df.rename(columns={'ageBroad': 'count'}, inplace=True)

# Displaying the pie chart of the percentage of female and male victims 
gender_pie_chart = gender_df.plot.pie(y='count', figsize=(5, 5), title="Victims by Gender", autopct='%1.1f%%')

As suspected, 73.3% of the victims of human trafficking represented in this dataset are female. However, a considerable amount of victims are male, contrary to misconceptions that people may hold regarding human trafficking victims.

Majority Status¶

Adult and children alike are victims of human trafficking. This pie chart seeks to visualize the majority status of the victims in this dataset, either as an adult or minor. A minor is any child under the age of 18.

In [8]:
# Creating a dataframe of the count of each status, 'Minor' and 'Adult'
status_df = pd.DataFrame(data.groupby('majorityStatus').count()['yearOfRegistration'])

# Renaming the column to represent the count 
status_df.rename(columns={'yearOfRegistration': 'count'}, inplace=True)

# Displaying the percentage of adults and minors in a pie chart
status_pie_chart = status_df.plot.pie(y='count', figsize=(5, 5), title="Victims by Majority Status", autopct='%1.1f%%')

According to the pie chart, 72% of human trafficking victims are adults while 28% are children. However, I would suspect that the percentage of children is low because children do not usually have as much documentation and methods of identification as adults, such as driver's licenses and any sort of online footprint. Many cases are unreported and this dataset does not encapsulate every human trafficking victim.

Types of Trafficking/Exploitation¶

Human trafficking involves different types of exploitation. The types observed in this dataset are:

  1. Forced Labor
  2. Sexual Exploit
  3. Other Exploit
  4. Sex and Labor
  5. Forced Marriage
  6. Forced Military
  7. Organ Removal
  8. Abduction
  9. Slavery and Practices

These graphs aim to visualize the number of each type of trafficking and how it changes over time.

In [9]:

Types of Exploitation over time¶

Different methods of exploitation can rise and fall over time and patterns can exist between the counts of exploitation over time. The following analysis aims to observe the possible trends and see how the counts of exploitation and the different types change over time.

In [12]:
# A dataframe of the counts of each type of exploit each year is created.
# The columns are first grouped by year and then each column is the aggregated sum of the count of that exploit for that year. 
exploit_year_df = pd.DataFrame(data.groupby('yearOfRegistration').agg(forced_labour=("isForcedLabour", np.sum), sexual_exploit=("isSexualExploit", np.sum), \
                                                                     other_exploit=("isOtherExploit", np.sum), sex_labour=("isSexAndLabour", np.sum), \
                                                                     forced_marriage=("isForcedMarriage", np.sum), forced_military=("isForcedMilitary", np.sum), \
                                                                     organ_removal=("isOrganRemoval", np.sum), abduction=("isAbduction", np.sum), \
                                                                      slavery=("isSlaveryAndPractices", np.sum)))

Country¶

Country is another feature in the dataset, with a victim's citizenship and the country of exploitation recorded in the dataset. Victims might be transported and exploited in a country they are not originally from or exploited in their own country. By looking at the patterns between citizenship and country of exploitation, further analysis can be conducted on attempting to predict these relationships or track victims.

Count by country¶

This analysis explores the differences in the number of human trafficking victims by country in which they were exploited in. These total counts are dispayed in a bar graph to visualize the differences between countries and to gain a greater perspective of the main places where many victims are exploited in.

Age and type of labor¶

Age can also be associated to the type of exploitation victims experience. The following analysis groups each age group and totals the number of victims for each type of exploitation, then plotting those totals in a line graph.

In [39]:
# A dataframe for the number of victims by age for each type of exploitation is created by grouping the victims 
# by the year and the exploitation and then counting how many fall in each category.

# Forced Labor count by age 
age_exploit_df = pd.DataFrame(data.groupby(['ageBroad', 'isForcedLabour']).count()['yearOfRegistration'])
age_exploit_df.rename(columns={"yearOfRegistration": "forcedLabourCount"}, inplace=True)

# Sexual exploit count by age
age_exploit_df['sexualExploitCount'] = data.groupby(['ageBroad', 'isSexualExploit']).count()['yearOfRegistration']

# Other exploit count by age
age_exploit_df['otherExploitCount'] = data.groupby(['ageBroad', 'isOtherExploit']).count()['yearOfRegistration']

# Sex and labor count by age
age_exploit_df['sexLaborCount'] = data.groupby(['ageBroad', 'isSexAndLabour']).count()['yearOfRegistration']

# Forced marriage by age
age_exploit_df['forcedMarriageCount'] = data.groupby(['ageBroad', 'isForcedMarriage']).count()['yearOfRegistration']

# Forced military by age
age_exploit_df['forcedMilitaryCount'] = data.groupby(['ageBroad', 'isForcedMilitary']).count()['yearOfRegistration']

# Organ removal by age
age_exploit_df['organRemovalCount'] = data.groupby(['ageBroad', 'isOrganRemoval']).count()['yearOfRegistration']

# Slavery count by age 
age_exploit_df['slaveryCount'] = data.groupby(['ageBroad', 'isSlaveryAndPractices']).count()['yearOfRegistration']

# Resetting index so age range is a separate column in the dataframe 
age_exploit_df.reset_index(inplace=True)

# Removing the counts of victims that did not undergo the exploitation. This is denoted by rows that represent the

Citizenship¶

The last feature we will analyze before moving onto the next phase of the data science pipeline is the citizenship of the victims. The citizenship can show the distribution of victims based on their home country and as a result, which residents of countries might be more vulnerable to trafficking. When citizenship is analyzed with country of exploitation, we can see the possible trends between where victims are from and where they tend to end up.

Citizenship summary¶

This summary visualizes the count of victims based on their citizenship as noted in the dataset.

This graph shows that most of the vitims are from or are citizens of PH, the Philippines. This is contrary to the country where victims are exploited the most, the United States, suggesting that the country of origin is not always the country of exploitation for trafficking victims.

Citizenship and Country of Exploitation pairs¶

Patterns can also exist among victim's country of origin and the country of exploitation, suggesting patterns of transportation that victims undergo. Often times victims in one country can be falsely promised a job and new life in a different country and end up agreeing on the premise of false promises. These victims often end up receiving little to no wage and are threatened by their exploiters.

The most frequent pairing is (00, US). A country code of 00 indicates that the country of citizenship is unknown and US represents the country of exploitation. This makes sense as we saw earlier that the US held the highest number of victims based on country of exploitation. The second highest pairing is (UA, UA) and the third is (MD, MD). These two also align with the analysis of the number of victims per country of exploitation as UA ranked second and MD ranked third highest in count. In these cases, many victims from UA and MD are exploited in their home country, showing that victims of trafficking are not always trafficked to another country but can be exploited right in their own country and even within their own community.

Machine Learning¶

Now, after exploring and analyzing the data and gaining a greater understanding of the distribution of the victims and what relationships may be present, it's time to apply that and see if we can model those relationships using machine learning algorithms. As mentioned before, there is a lot of missing data in the dataset and in datasets concerning human trafficking in general. In this case, the data could be Missing at Random (MAR) due to confounding variables that affect whether information is recorded and reported or not. The data could also be Missing Not at Random (MNAR) because it is information regarding victims which can be sensitive and could give away their identity. Especially for victims who might have escaped or been rescued, their information is sensitive and might not have been included in the dataset or other trafficking datasets for safety reasons.

In an attempt to deal with the missing data and predict what it might be, I employed the machine learning algorithms of imputation and random forest classification to impute the missing values for the types of exploitation based on the remaining features in the dataset. Let's take a look at how we can accomplish this with libraries from SkLearn.

Modelling the Type of Exploitation¶

Missing values are imputed and a model is created with random forest. Iterative (multivariate) Imputing is used to impute missing values in the dataset. Multivariate imputation was chosen over univariate imputation because multivarite imputation uses all available features to estimate the missing values and not just one feature like univariate imputation. However, one drawback of using multivariate imputation is that it is still experiemental and its behavior might change as SKLearn resolves its issues.

Please refer to SKLearn's page about imputation for more information regarding imputation and any changes in the future to multivariate imputation: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/impute.html

Once values are imputed, the second step is to model the data with random forest. Random Forest is a supervised machine learning algorithm that can handle classification problems by building a 'forest' of decision trees to result in a single output/decision. A forest of decision trees is more robust than just one decision tree, reducing the risk of overfitting. A trade-off of this algorithm however is the time it takes to complete and the complexity of the result, as opposed to a decision tree that does not take as much time and results in only one result and not one result for each tree. Because the algorithm is slow, I changed the number of trees generated in the forest to 50 instead of the default of 100 trees. Random forests can still overfitt the data if they are not pruned and if other parameters are not tuned to control the way trees are grown. As a result, I limited the max_depth of each tree to 5.

Check out this page to learn more about random forests and gain a high level view of the concepts: https://www.ibm.com/cloud/learn/random-forest

This pipeline of imputation and modelling is then evaluated using 10-fold cross-valdation instead of just a split of the data into training and testing data in order to estimate the skill of the model with less bias and to test the model on more than one test set. For this tutorial, I am using repeated strafified k-Fold cross-validation. Stratified validation ensures that the data is split into proportional parts and repeated validation repeats the process however many times specified, in this case three times, and the data is split differently each time.

Here is a resource on k-Fold Cross-Validation and the different types that exist to learn further: https://machinelearningmastery.com/k-fold-cross-validation/

The last step is to attempt to predict if an individual is a victim of a certain exploitation or not based on the pipeline of iterative imputation and random forest modelling of the existing data. As a result, we can create a model that predicts what type of exploitation an individual might be a victim of based on the other features present in the dataset.

Standardizing the Data¶

The dataset contains non-numeric data values, such as the countries, ages, and gender to name a few features. Therefore, those categorical variables must be converted to numbers in order to perform the machine learning algorithms as outlined above on the data. In order to do this, I apply SKLearn's LabelEncoder() from the preprocessing library to transform string labels to numberic values.

There are originally 63 features in the dataset. However, due to the limited memory and the the time it takes to perform the machine learning algorithms, I limited the features to the ones that have been analyzed in the exploratory data analysis step earlier, in addition to the features that describe the means of control regarding each victim. I chose to include the means of control because the type of exploitation a victim faces can be dependent on the way the perpetrator is controlling them.

Forced Labor¶

Now that the dataset is ready for processing, we first start by imputing the missing values for the forced labor feature of the dataset based on the other remaining features and then model using random forest. In evaluating that model, we can see how accurate the model is. Using this same pipeline, we can try to predict and classify if an individual whose data for the 'isForcedLabour' column is NaN is a victim of forced labor or not.

In [48]:
# Dropping rows with NaN in isForcedLabour column for the machine learning algorithm to impute on
df = data_table.dropna(subset=['isForcedLabour'], how='all')
In [49]:
# Creating the pipeline of imputation to random forest modelling of the dataset
# 10-fold cross-validation is applied to this pipeline to reduce the bias of the evaulation of the model/pipeline

df_values = df.values
# X_labor represents the input feature (all other features besides isForcedLabour)
# y_labor represents the output feature (isForcedLabour)
index = [i for i in range(table.shape[1]) if i != 26]
X_labor, y_labor = df_values[:, index], df_values[:, 26]
# creating the pipeline of iterative imputation to random forest modelling
model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=50, max_depth=5)
imputer = IterativeImputer()
pipeline = Pipeline(steps=[('i', imputer), ('m', model)])
# Define model evaluation
cv = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=10, n_repeats=3, random_state=1)
# Evaluate model
scores = cross_val_score(pipeline, X_labor.tolist(), y_labor.tolist(), scoring='accuracy', cv=cv, n_jobs=-1, error_score='raise')
# Print the mean accuracy of the model based on the scores received from the cross-validation
print('Mean Accuracy: %.3f (%.3f)' % (np.mean(scores), np.std(scores)))

Mean Accuracy: 0.982 (0.003)

We have evaulated the accuracy of the model as 98.3%, which is very high. This is likely due to some overfitting of the model on the dataset and can be adjusted by tuning the parameters. However, we will continue on to predict the missing values in the isForcedLabour column and classify if that victim experienced forced labor or not.

In order to do this, the NaN rows of the column must be dropped temporarily and used as the test data for the pipeline. The training dataset is subsequently the non-NaN rows of the column that the pipeline will use to fit on. The test data is then treated as new data to be predicted on.

Conclusion¶

Concluding Thoughts¶

Reliable and non-missing human trafficking data can be difficult to obtain and therefore perform analysis on. Despite these challenges often seen in the real world, this tutorial walked through the stages of the data science pipeline in analyzing possible relationships that occur in existing data and attempting to predict missing values to use in further anaysis.

The data was first gathered and read into a dataframe as part of the data collection and management step. Missing values were accounted for and the dataframe was ready for manipulation and anlysis. Then, the data was explored to visualize the patterns and trends in the data. I analyzed some of the main features of the dataset including age, gender, and type of exploitation. Sexual exploitation was the most common type of exploitation observed in the dataset and the United States was the most frequent country exploitation took place. This step allowed us to fiddle with the data and inform what should be done in the next step: machine learning. The exploratory data analysis lead to an interest in what missing values would be classified as based on the existing data and how those classifications would or would not change the distribution of the data. Therefore, a pipeline of imputation and random forest classification was implemented to predict what missing values in respect to the types of exploitation would be.

As a result of predicting the missing values of the types of exploitation victims experienced, we observed that there are potentially a lot more victims of each type of exploitation and trafficking than what the original dataset communicated. This highlights that the missing data is not insignificant and we cannot see the complete picture without the missing data, or in this case the predicted missing values. Data is extremely powerful and with it we can communicate to society how immense this crime is and how devastating human trafficking is in our world.

Further Application¶

This tutorial can be extended futher to attempt to predict other missing features in the dataset. One of these features could be the country of exploitation and the country of citizenship. If machine learning algorithms are employed on the relationships between the countries, then it could be possible to predict the routes in which perpetrators transport or send trafficked victims and the different clusters that may exist.

In the end, analyzing human trafficking data should help in rescuing and helping trafficked victims and trying to break the cycle of trafficking by catching perpetrators in the middle.
